While I agree that strong typed keys would be very helpful in i18next, there are two reasons why this is not possible:

1.) TypeScript has no way to evaluate [dynamic/computed string expressions][1] like `&#39;footer.copyright&#39;`, so that `footer` and `copyright` could be identified as key parts in the translations object hierarchy.

2.) react i18next `useTranslation` API works with strings (compare types [here][2] and [here][3]) and does not enforce type dependencies to your defined dictionary/translations. Instead `t` function contains generic type parameters, which default to `string` or similar widened types, when not manually specified.

---

Knowing that you rather don&#39;t want to use a wrapper, here is just a demonstration sample I put together some time ago which makes use of Rest parameters/tuples.

Typed `t` function:
```
type Dictionary = string | DictionaryObject;
type DictionaryObject = { [K: string]: Dictionary };

interface TypedTFunction&lt;D extends Dictionary&gt; {
    &lt;K extends keyof D&gt;(args: K): D[K];
    &lt;K extends keyof D, K1 extends keyof D[K]&gt;(...args: [K, K1]): D[K][K1];
    &lt;K extends keyof D, K1 extends keyof D[K], K2 extends keyof D[K][K1]&gt;(
        ...args: [K, K1, K2]
    ): D[K][K1][K2];
    // ... up to a reasonable key parameters length of your choice ...
}
```
Typed `useTranslation` Hook:
```
import { useTranslation } from &#39;react-i18next&#39;;

type MyTranslations = {/* your concrete type*/}
// e.g. via const dict = {...}; export type MyTranslations = typeof dict

// import this hook in other modules instead of i18next useTranslation
export function useTypedTranslation(): { t: TypedTFunction&lt;typeof dict&gt; } {
  const { t } = useTranslation();
  // implementation goes here: join keys by dot (depends on your config)
  // and delegate to lib t
  return { t(...keys: string[]) { return t(keys.join(&quot;.&quot;)) } }  
}
```
Import `useTypedTranslation` in other modules:
```
import { useTypedTranslation } from &quot;./useTypedTranslation&quot;

const App = () =&gt; {
  const { t } = useTypedTranslation()
  return &lt;div&gt;{t(&quot;footer&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;)}&lt;/div&gt;
}
```
Test it:
```
const res1 = t(&quot;footer&quot;); // const res1: { &quot;copyright&quot;: string;}
const res2 = t(&quot;footer&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;); // const res2: string
const res3 = t(&quot;footer&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;, &quot;lala&quot;); // error, OK
const res4 = t(&quot;lala&quot;); // error, OK
const res5 = t(&quot;footer&quot;, &quot;lala&quot;); // error, OK
```
[Playground][8]

You potentially could [infer][5] those types automatically with [recursive types][4] instead of the multiple overload signatures above. But [in this case][6] the TS team [does not recommend them for production][7], so I present the latter here.

Hope, it helps.

  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/57653776/how-to-match-string-literal-type-when-concat-string-in-typescript/57654524
  [2]: https://github.com/i18next/react-i18next/blob/master/src/index.d.ts#L57
  [3]: https://github.com/i18next/i18next/blob/master/index.d.ts#L628
  [4]: https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/pull/33050
  [5]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-8.html#type-inference-in-conditional-types
  [6]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/?ts=3.7-Beta&amp;ssl=1&amp;ssc=1&amp;pln=27&amp;pc=64#-QHiWmYLD4YjsqBILAjBoIMIIogCkV2UK9CKBfQ8PQBtJ6JqAPSdmDF6AwMsVyjweIyxIAbh4fdL5YATFXWbXyvXkI30WwW22yB2YN3e+B+4PZ-mEUYgA
  [7]: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/24897#issuecomment-401418254
